BLOEMFONTEIN Celtic coach John Maduka is looking to mastermind an upset of epic proportions against Absa Premiership leaders Kaizer Chiefs. Phunya Sele Sele will welcome the high-flying Amakhosi at their home away from home, the Absa Tuks Stadium, tomorrow (6pm). Celtic head into this clash unbeaten since the restart having beaten Baroka FC 3-0 in the Nedbank Cup and played out to a 1-1 draw against SuperSport United in the league on Sunday. Maduka, who took over the reigns at Celtic following the departure of Lehlohonolo Seema who joined Chippa United, has picked up from where his predecessor left off. He has not changed much in the way that Celtic play, insisting that there was no point trying to fix what was not broken. Celtic, who are currently 11th on the log, are still well in the race for a top eight finish which would be considered a successful season for the Free State outfit. Chiefs, on the other hand, will provide arguably the toughest test for Maduka since stepping onto the hot-seat at Celtic. But the Malawian is relishing the prospect of stopping Amakhosi dead on their tracks as they eye their first Premiership title since the 2013-14 season. Maduka, having watched CONTINUED ON PAGE 14